18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
19 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
20 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 200 of Title 75A, unless there
21 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
22 A. This act shall be known and may be cited as the “Oklahoma AI
23 Education Innovation Act”.
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 1

1 B. As used in this act, “artificial intelligence” or “AI” means
2 a system or application consistent with the definition set forth in
3 15 U.S.C., Section 9401(3).
4 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
5 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
6 The Legislature finds that:
7 1. Artificial intelligence is transforming education, workforce
8 development, and economic opportunity across the United States and
9 around the world;
10 2. The State of Oklahoma requires coordinated investment across
11 K-12 education, higher education, career and technology education,
12 and public libraries to ensure that students, educators, and the
13 workforce are prepared for the opportunities and challenges
14 presented by artificial intelligence;
15 3. Research conducted in this state regarding the impact of
16 artificial intelligence on education and workforce development
17 enables the state to be more responsive in both funding and
18 implementation of artificial intelligence education initiatives; and
19 4. A dedicated fund and advisory structure are necessary to
20 ensure that Oklahoma’s investments in artificial intelligence
21 education are strategic, coordinated, and accountable.
22 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 201 of Title 75A, unless there
24 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
Req. No. 3980 Page 2

1 A. There is hereby created in the State Treasury a revolving
2 fund to be designated the “Oklahoma AI Education Innovation
3 Revolving Fund”. The fund shall be a continuing fund, not subject
4 to fiscal year limitations, and shall consist of:
5 1. All monies appropriated to the fund by the Legislature;
6 2. All monies received from gifts, grants, reimbursements, or
7 other contributions from public or private sources for purposes
8 consistent with this act, provided that all such gifts, grants, and
9 contributions shall be designated by the donor, grantor, or
10 contributing entity for distribution to one or more specific agency
11 accounts within the fund prior to acceptance. Federal funds
12 received by an agency designated in this act for purposes consistent
13 with this act may be deposited into the agency’s account within the
14 fund, subject to applicable federal requirements;
15 3. Any interest or investment earnings attributable to monies
16 in the fund; and
17 4. Any other monies designated for deposit in the fund.
18 B. Upon the effective date of this act, the State Treasurer
19 shall establish and maintain within the Oklahoma AI Education
20 Innovation Revolving Fund a separate account for each of the
21 following agencies:
22 1. The State Department of Education;
23 2. The Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education;
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 3

1 3. The Oklahoma Department of Career and Technology Education;
2 and
3 4. The Oklahoma Department of Libraries.
4 C. Legislative appropriations to the fund shall specify the
5 dollar amount to be deposited to each agency account. Monies
6 received from gifts, grants, reimbursements, or other nonlegislative
7 sources shall be deposited to the agency account designated by the
8 donor, grantor, or contributing entity. Interest and investment
9 earnings shall be allocated to each agency account in proportion to
10 the average daily balance of each account during the preceding
11 fiscal quarter.
12 D. All monies accruing to the credit of the fund are hereby
13 appropriated and may be budgeted and expended by each agency from
14 its designated account within the fund for the purposes provided in
15 subsection F of this section. Expenditures from the fund shall be
16 made upon warrants issued by the State Treasurer against claims
17 filed as prescribed by law with the Director of the Office of
18 Management and Enterprise Services for approval and payment.
19 E. Each agency may seek and accept gifts, grants, and
20 contributions from public and private sources for deposit in its
21 account within the fund, consistent with the purposes of this act.
22 F. Monies in agency accounts within the Oklahoma AI Education
23 Innovation Revolving Fund shall be expended by the designated
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 4

1 agen cies solely for one or more of the following purposes related to
2 artificial intelligence in education:
3 1. Development, acquisition, and implementation of artificial
4 intelligence tools, platforms, and resources for educational use;
5 2. Professional development and training for educators,
6 administrators, librarians, and staff on the effective and ethical
7 use of artificial intelligence in educational settings;
8 3. Curriculum development integrating artificial intelligence,
9 digital literacy, and computational thinking;
10 4. Research and evaluation of the impact of artificial
11 intelligence on education, student welfare and safety, the educator
12 workforce, educational communities, and workforce development;
13 5. Student programs and initiatives promoting artificial
14 intelligence literacy and workforce readiness;
15 6. Infrastructure improvements necessary to support artificial
16 intelligence educational initiatives;
17 7. Public awareness and community education programs regarding
18 artificial intelligence; and
19 8. Administrative costs directly related to the purposes
20 enumerated in this subsection, provided that no more than ten
21 percent (10%) of any agency’s funds received during the fiscal year
22 may be expended for administrative costs.
23 G. No later than October 1 of each year, each agency designated
24 in this act shall electronically submit a report to the President
Req. No. 3980 Page 5

1 Pro Tempore of the Senate, the Speaker of the House of
2 Representatives, the Governor, and the Oklahoma AI Education
3 Advisory Council created in Section 4 of this act detailing:
4 1. The total amount of monies received pursuant to this act
5 during the preceding fiscal year, organized by funding source;
6 2. An accounting of all expenditures made from such monies,
7 organized by funding source and by the applicable purpose categories
8 specified in this act;
9 3. The outcomes achieved through such expenditures;
10 4. Any unexpended balances and the intended use of such
11 balances;
12 5. Recommended improvements or modifications to the agency’s
13 artificial intelligence education initiatives;
14 6. A description of the cost-sharing agreement for
15 administrative support of the Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council
16 and the costs incurred by the agency pursuant to such agreement;
17 7. The identity of all donors and grantors contributing monies
18 to the agency’s account within the fund, the amounts contributed,
19 any conditions or restrictions attached to such contributions, and
20 any relationships between donors or grantors and providers of
21 artificial intelligence products or services utilized by the agency;
22 and
23
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 6

1 8. A description of the agency’s efforts to ensure equitable
2 access to artificial intelligence education resources across
3 geographic, economic, and demographic populations in this state.
4 H. Reports required by subsection G of this section shall
5 include a consolidated accounting of all monies received and
6 expended pursuant to this act, regardless of funding source,
7 including, but not limited to, state appropriations, federal funds,
8 and public or private gifts, grants, and contributions.
9 I. In expending monies pursuant to this act, each agency shall
10 give consideration to ensuring equitable access to artificial
11 intelligence education resources across geographic, economic, and
12 demographic populations in this state.
13 J. Two or more agencies designated in this act may enter into
14 interagency agreements for the purpose of jointly funding or
15 implementing artificial intelligence education initiatives
16 consistent with this act, with costs shared from their respective
17 accounts. Any such agreements and the expenditures made pursuant to
18 such agreements shall be reported to the Oklahoma AI Education
19 Advisory Council and included in the annual reports required by
20 subsection G of this section.
21 K. All activities undertaken pursuant to this act involving
22 student data shall comply with the Family Educational Rights and
23 Privacy Act of 1974 (FERPA), 20 U.S.C., Section 1232g, and any other
24 applicable state and federal privacy requirements.
Req. No. 3980 Page 7

1 L. Intellectual property created with monies from the Oklahoma
2 AI Education Innovation Revolving Fund shall be made available to
3 all agencies and institutions designated in this act on a
4 nonexclusive, royalty-free basis.
5 M. Artificial intelligence tools and platforms acquired or
6 developed pursuant to this act shall be accessible to individuals
7 with disabilities in accordance with applicable federal and state
8 law.
9 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 202 of Title 75A, unless there
11 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. There is hereby created, to continue until July 1, 2031, in
13 accordance with the provisions of the Oklahoma Sunset Law, the
14 Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council. The Council shall consist
15 of nineteen (19) members as follows:
16 1. The Superintendent of Public Instruction serving as an ex
17 officio voting member, or designee;
18 2. The Chancellor of Higher Education serving as an ex officio
19 voting member, or designee;
20 3. The Director of the Oklahoma Department of Career and
21 Technology Education serving as an ex officio voting member, or
22 designee;
23 4. The Director of the Oklahoma Department of Libraries serving
24 as an ex officio voting member, or designee;
Req. No. 3980 Page 8

1 5. The Secretary of Education serving as an ex officio voting
2 member, or designee;
3 6. One member appointed by the Governor with experience in
4 artificial intelligence research or development;
5 7. One member appointed by the Governor with experience in
6 kindergarten through twelfth grade education;
7 8. One member appointed by the Governor with experience in
8 workforce development;
9 9. One member appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the
10 Senate with experience in higher education;
11 10. One member appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the
12 Senate with experience in educational technology;
13 11. One member appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the
14 Senate who is a current Senator with consideration of service on the
15 Oklahoma Education Commission;
16 12. One member appointed by the Speaker of the House of
17 Representatives with experience in business or industry utilizing
18 artificial intelligence;
19 13. One member appointed by the Speaker of the House of
20 Representatives with experience in rural education;
21 14. One member appointed by the Speaker of the House of
22 Representatives who is a current House member with consideration of
23 service on the Oklahoma Education Commission;
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 9

1 15. One member who is a current classroom teacher, appointed
2 jointly by the Superintendent of Public Instruction and the
3 Chancellor of Higher Education;
4 16. One member who is a current public school administrator,
5 appointed by the Superintendent of Public Instruction;
6 17. One member who is a current faculty member at an
7 institution within The Oklahoma State System of Higher Education,
8 appointed by the Chancellor of Higher Education;
9 18. One member representing Oklahoma tribal nations with
10 interest in educational technology, appointed by the Governor in
11 consultation with the Oklahoma Native American Liaison; and
12 19. One member representing the Oklahoma business community,
13 appointed by the Governor.
14 B. 1. The five ex officio members designated in paragraphs 1
15 through 5 of subsection A of this section shall serve for the
16 duration of their time in office.
17 2. After initial terms of office set forth in paragraph 3 of
18 this subsection, the terms of office of appointed members shall be
19 for three (3) years. Appointed members may only serve two terms on
20 the Council.
21 3. Initial appointments shall be as follows:
22 a. members appointed pursuant to paragraphs 6, 9, 12, 15,
23 and 18 of subsection A of this section shall serve
24 initial terms of three (3) years,
Req. No. 3980 Page 10

1 b. members appointed pursuant to paragraphs 7, 10, 11,
2 13, and 16 of subsection A of this section shall serve
3 initial terms of two (2) years, and
4 c. members appointed pursuant to paragraphs 8, 14, 17,
5 and 19 of subsection A of this section shall serve
6 initial terms of one (1) year.
7 4. Vacancies shall be filled for any unexpired term in the same
8 manner as the original appointment.
9 5. Members shall serve their terms at the pleasure of the
10 appointing authority and may be removed or replaced without cause.
11 C. Members of the Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council shall
12 be exempt from the dual-office-holding prohibitions of Section 6 of
13 Title 51 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
14 D. Members of the Council shall receive no compensation for
15 their service but shall be reimbursed for necessary travel expenses
16 incurred in the performance of their duties in accordance with the
17 State Travel Reimbursement Act.
18 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 203 of Title 75A, unless there
20 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. The Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council created in
22 Section 4 of this act shall:
23 1. Advise and make recommendations to the State Department of
24 Education, the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education, the
Req. No. 3980 Page 11

1 Okla homa Department of Career and Technology Education, and the
2 Oklahoma Department of Libraries on matters relating to:
3 a. the development and implementation of artificial
4 intelligence education initiatives,
5 b. coordination among agencies to maximize the
6 effectiveness of artificial intelligence education
7 investments,
8 c. best practices for integrating artificial intelligence
9 into curriculum and instruction,
10 d. ethical considerations and responsible use of
11 artificial intelligence in educational settings,
12 e. workforce preparation for careers involving artificial
13 intelligence, and
14 f. digital literacy and equitable access to artificial
15 intelligence educational resources;
16 2. Review the annual reports submitted by agencies pursuant to
17 this act and provide feedback and recommendations;
18 3. Identify gaps, redundancies, or opportunities for
19 collaboration among agencies designated in this act;
20 4. Monitor national and international trends in artificial
21 intelligence education and make recommendations for Oklahoma to
22 remain competitive;
23
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 12

1 5. Engage with stakeholders including educators, students,
2 parents, employers, and community members to gather input on
3 artificial intelligence education needs and priorities;
4 6. Develop and recommend metrics for evaluating the
5 effectiveness of artificial intelligence education initiatives
6 funded pursuant to this act; and
7 7. Perform such other advisory duties as may be requested by
8 the Legislature, the Governor, or the agencies designated in this
9 act.
10 B. The Council shall have no authority to direct, control, or
11 supervise the operations of any state agency, institution, or school
12 district. All recommendations of the Council shall be advisory only
13 and shall not be binding on any agency or institution.
14 C. No later than December 1 of each year, the Council shall
15 electronically submit an annual report to the President Pro Tempore
16 of the Senate, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, the
17 Governor, the State Board of Education, the Oklahoma State Regents
18 for Higher Education, the Oklahoma Department of Career and
19 Technology Education, and the Oklahoma Department of Libraries. The
20 report shall include:
21 1. A summary of Council activities during the preceding year;
22 2. An assessment of the progress of artificial intelligence
23 education initiatives across all designated agencies;
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 13

1 3. Findings and recommendations for improving coordination and
2 effectiveness;
3 4. Identification of emerging opportunities or challenges in
4 artificial intelligence education;
5 5. Any recommended legislative or administrative actions; and
6 6. Recommended appropriation levels and funding sources for the
7 next fiscal year.
8 D. The report provided for in subsection C of this section
9 shall be publicly posted on the websites for the State Department of
10 Education, the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education, the
11 Oklahoma Department of Career and Technology Education, and the
12 Oklahoma Department of Libraries.
13 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
14 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 204 of Title 75A, unless there
15 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
16 A. The Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council created in
17 Section 4 of this act shall meet at least quarterly at the call of
18 the chair. Additional meetings may be called by the chair or upon
19 written request of a majority of the members.
20 B. At its first meeting, the Council shall elect from among its
21 members a chair and a vice chair who shall serve for terms of two
22 (2) years. The chair and vice chair may be reelected for one
23 additional term but shall not serve more than two terms.
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 14

1 C. A majority of the members of the Council shall constitute a
2 quorum for the transaction of business. All official actions of the
3 Council shall require the affirmative vote of a majority of those
4 members present and voting.
5 D. The Council may establish subcommittees as it deems
6 necessary to carry out its duties.
7 E. All meetings of the Council and its subcommittees shall be
8 subject to the Oklahoma Open Meeting Act and the Oklahoma Open
9 Records Act.
10 F. The State Department of Education, the Oklahoma State
11 Regents for Higher Education, the Oklahoma Department of Career and
12 Technology Education, and the Oklahoma Department of Libraries shall
13 provide administrative and staff support, information, and
14 assistance to the Council upon request. The agencies shall
15 determine among themselves the sharing of costs for administrative
16 and staff support of the Council and shall include a description of
17 such cost-sharing agreement and the costs incurred in the annual
18 report required by Section 3 of this act.
19 G. Any member of the Council who has a financial interest in a
20 matter before the Council shall disclose such interest and shall
21 recuse himself or herself from any deliberation or vote on such
22 matter.
23
24
Req. No. 3980 Page 15

1 H. The Council, through its chair or designee, shall be
2 available to present findings and recommendations to legislative
3 committees upon request.
4 SECTION 7. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
5 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
6 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
7 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
